'''Tulsa''' is the second-largest city in the U.S. state of [[Oklahoma]]. It is the [[county seat]] of [[Tulsa County, Oklahoma|Tulsa County]], the most densely populated county in Oklahoma, with 563,299 residents as of the [[United States Census 2000|2000 census]]. As of 2006, Tulsa had an estimated population of 387,807,<ref> {{cite web | url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/40/4075000.html | title=Tulsa (city) QuickFacts | publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] | accessdate=2007-04-25}}</ref> and its [[Metropolitan Statistical Area]] had an estimated population of 897,752. In 2007, the U.S. Census Bureau projected the Tulsa MSA to reach 1 million residents within three to five years.<ref name="Metro growth nearing 7 digits">{{cite web | date=4-5-2007 | url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/article.aspx?articleID=070405_1_A1_hThes35833 | title= Metro Area growth nearing 7 digits| format=web | work=Leigh Bell| pages=1 | publisher=Tulsa World | accessdate=2007-04-13}}</ref> As of 2006, Tulsa’s [[Combined Statistical Area]], which includes the Bartlesville Micropolitan Area, was estimated to have a population of 946,993. Tulsa is the 46th largest city in the [[United States]]<ref name=PopEstBigCities>{{cite web | url = http://www.census.gov/popest/cities/tables/SUB-EST2005-01.csv | title = Table 1: Annual Estimates of the Population for Incorporated Places Over 100,000, Ranked by July 1, 2005 Population: April 1, 2000 to July 1, 2005 | format = [[comma-separated values|CSV]] | work = 2005 Population Estimates | publisher = [[United States Census Bureau]], Population Division | date = [[2006-06-20]] | accessdate = 2007-04-20 }}</ref> and the 93rd largest city in [[North America]].

Tulsa was first settled by the [[Creek]] [[Native American]] tribe during the early [[19th Century]] after the [[Trail of Tears|forced removal]] of the [[five civilized tribes]] into [[Indian Territory]] and what would later become the state of Oklahoma. In the early 20th Century, the city became one of the most important oil centers in the United States. Still a significant energy center, modern Tulsa is also a hub for aviation, telecommunications and technology.<ref name="Work in Tulsa">{{cite web | date=2006 | url=http://tulsaok.usachamber.com/custom2.asp?pageid=1190 | title= Business Opportunities| format=web | work=Tulsa Metro Chamber of Commerce | pages=1 | publisher= Tulsa Metro Chamber of Commerce | accessdate=2006-04-14}}</ref> The [[Tulsa Port of Catoosa]] is one of the nation's largest seaports and the most inland port in the United States.<ref name="Tulsa Port of Catoosa">{{cite web | date=2007 | url= http://www.tulsaport.com/profile.html | title= Port of Catoosa Profile| format=web | work=Tulsa Port of Catoosa| pages=1 | publisher=Tulsa Port of Catoosa| accessdate=2006-04-22}}</ref> Two private institutions of higher education that participate at the NCAA Divison 1 level are located in Tulsa: the [[University of Tulsa]] and [[Oral Roberts University]]. The city will also be the site of the world's largest free-standing [[statue]], "[[The American]]," which will break ground in 2007 with an expected completion in 2011.<ref name="'The American' Progressing">{{cite web | date=2007-04-24 | url=http://kotv.com/news/local/story/?id=125807| title= Progress On The American Slow But Steady | format=web | work=KOTV| pages=1 | publisher=KOTV | accessdate=2007-04-28}}</ref> The monument is anticipated by developers to be a national icon similar to the [[Gateway Arch]], [[Mount Rushmore]], and the [[Statue of Liberty]].<ref name="Vision 2025: The American">{{cite web | year=2007 | url=http://www.vision2025.info/category.php?category=theamerican| title= The American| format=web | work=Vision 2025 Commission| pages=1 | publisher=Vision 2025 Commission| accessdate=2007-04-28}}</ref>

Tulsa is located in Northeast Oklahoma, a part of the state often referred to as "[[Green Country]]." It is considered the cultural and arts center of Oklahoma,<ref name="Our City - Tulsa">{{cite web | year=2005 | url=http://www.cityoftulsa.org/OurCity/| title=Our City | work=City of Tulsa | publisher=City of Tulsa | accessdate=2007-04-22}}</ref> boasting two world-renowned art museums, full-time professional opera and ballet companies, and one of the nation's largest concentrations of [[art deco]] architecture.<ref name="Quality of Life">{{cite web | date=2006 | url=http://www.okcommerce.gov/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=332&Itemid=413 | title= Quality of Life - Fun and Play| format=web | work=Oklahoma Department of Commerce| pages=1 | publisher=Oklahoma Department of Commerce | accessdate=2006-07-15}}</ref> In 2005, Tulsa was selected as one of "America's Most Livable Large Cities."<ref name="Most Livable">{{cite web | date=2006 | url=http://www.mostlivable.org/cities/tulsa/home.html| title= Tulsa, Oklahoma | format=web | work=Most Livable| pages=1 | publisher=About Partners | accessdate=2006-07-15}}</ref> People from Tulsa are called ''Tulsans''.

== History ==
{{main|History of Tulsa, Oklahoma}}
[[Image:Meadowgold.jpg|thumb|left|The Meadow Gold sign greeted Route 66 travelers in Tulsa for decades.]]
What was to ultimately become Tulsa was originally part of [[Indian Territory]] and was first settled by the Lochapoka and Creek tribes in 1836.<ref name="Tulsa Area History">{{cite web | date=2007 | url= http://www.tulsalibrary.org/tulsahistory/communities.htm#tul| title=Tulsa Area History | format=web | work=Tulsa County Library| pages=1 | publisher= Tulsa County Library| accessdate=2007-04-25}}</ref> They established a home under a large oak tree at the present day intersection of Cheyenne Avenue and 18th Street, and named their new settlement "Tallasi," meaning "old town" in the Creek language, which led to the present day usage of the name "Tulsa."<ref name="Tulsa Area History">{{cite web | date=2007 | url= http://www.tulsalibrary.org/tulsahistory/communities.htm#tul| title=Tulsa Area History | format=web | work=Tulsa County Library| pages=1 | publisher= Tulsa County Library| accessdate=2007-04-25}}</ref> On January 18, 1898, Tulsa was officially incorporated, and elected its first mayor, Edward Calkins.<ref name="Tulsa County History">{{cite web | date=2005-09-15 | url= http://www.rootsweb.com/~oktulsa/history.htm| title=Tulsa County History | format=web | work=Roots Web| pages=1 | publisher= Roots Web| accessdate=2007-04-27}}</ref> 

In 1901, Tulsa was sleepy town near the banks of the [[Arkansas River]]. Its first oil well, named Sue Bland No. 1,<ref name="Tulsa County History">{{cite web | date=2005-09-15 | url= http://www.rootsweb.com/~oktulsa/history.htm| title=Tulsa County History | format=web | work=Roots Web| pages=1 | publisher= Roots Web| accessdate=2007-04-27}}</ref> was established that year. However, by 1905, the discovery of a large oil pool near the town of [[Glenpool, Oklahoma|Glenpool]] had prompted thousands of fortune seekers to find claims to one of the area's growing number of oil fields. In [[1900]], Census data tallied the population of Tulsa at 1,390; by [[1930]], the city's population had swelled to over 140,000 people.<ref name="Population of the 100 Largest Cities and Other Urban Places in the United States: 1790 to 1990">{{cite web | date=2005-09-15 | url=http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0027.html | title= Population of the 100 Largest Cities and Other Urban Places in the United States: 1790 to 1990| format=web | work=Campbell Gibson| pages=1 | accessdate=2007-04-29}}</ref> The "oil boom" led to an immense economic surge, earning the city the nickname "Oil Capital of the World" for most of the 20th century.<ref name="Tulsa History">{{cite web | date=2007 | url= http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=travel&res=950DE2D71131F934A1575BC0A96F948260| title= What's Doing in Tulsa?| format=web | work=Susan Everly-Douze | pages=1 | publisher= New York Times | accessdate=2007-04-14}}</ref> Money flowing from oil barons and their patrons prompted a building boom in the fist half of the 20th Century, as oil riches were used to construct a large number of buildings in the popular [[Art Deco]] style of the time. Profits from this oil boom continued well into the depression, helping Tulsa's economy fare much better than most cities in the United States during the 1930's.<ref name="Art Deco in Tulsa">{{cite web | date=2007 | url=http://www.tulsalibrary.org/research/artdeco/artdecointulsa.htm| title= What's Doing in Tulsa?| format=web | work=Rex Ball Jennifer Young| pages=1 | publisher= Tulsa City-County Library | accessdate=2007-04-25}}</ref>
[[Image:Tulsa-riot-fire.jpg|thumb|right|Dozens of blocks of "Black Wall Street" burned to the ground in the Tulsa Race Riot of 1921.]]
In the 1910's and 1920's, Tulsa was home to one of the largest and most prosperous [[African American]] communities in the United States.<ref name="Tulsa Race Riot">{{cite web | date=2007 | url= http://www.tulsareparations.org/TulsaRiot.htm| title= The Tulsa Race Riot| format=web | work=Scott Ellsworth| pages=1 | publisher= Tulsa Reparations | accessdate=2007-04-20}}</ref> Known as [[Black Wall Street]], it was located in the [[Greenwood, Tulsa, Oklahoma|Greenwood]] neighborhood of north Tulsa and was the site of a large [[race riot]] in [[1921]]. Known as the [[Tulsa Race Riot]], the violence that spread into the Greenwood neighborhood was one of the nation's worst acts of racial violence and large-scale civil disorder.<ref name="Tulsa Race Riot">{{cite web | date=2007 | url= http://www.tulsareparations.org/TulsaRiot.htm| title= The Tulsa Race Riot| format=web | work=Scott Ellsworth| pages=1 | publisher= Tulsa Reparations | accessdate=2007-04-20}}</ref>  From May 31 to June 1, 1921 during 16 hours of rioting, 39 people were officially reported killed, over 800 people were admitted to local hospitals with injuries, an estimated 10,000 were left homeless, 35 city blocks composed of 1,256 residences were destroyed by fire, and $1.8 million was caused in property damage.<ref name="Tulsa Race Riot">{{cite web | date=2007 | url= http://www.tulsareparations.org/TulsaRiot.htm| title= The Tulsa Race Riot| format=web | work=Scott Ellsworth| pages=1 | publisher= Tulsa Reparations | accessdate=2007-04-20}}</ref> Confined mainly to the segregated Greenwood neighborhood of Tulsa, the riot was responsible for wiping out nearly all of the prosperity and success that Black Wall Street had achieved until the area was partially rebuilt.

During the remainder of the mid-20th century, oil profits and an increasing aviation industry propelled the city to another economic surge. The new prosperity led to the development of a master plan for the city, which used a booming economy as the means to fund numerous parks, churches, museums, rose gardens, improved infrastructure, and increased national advertising. During [[World War II]], Tulsa become an important maintenance center for American Airlines and numerous other aviation related businesses that continued to pour money into the city's revitalization efforts. In the 1950's, Time magazine dubbed Tulsa "America's Most Beautiful City."<ref name="Tulsa History">{{cite web | date=2007 | url= http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=travel&res=950DE2D71131F934A1575BC0A96F948260| title= What's Doing in Tulsa?| format=web | work=Susan Everly-Douze | pages=1 | publisher= New York Times | accessdate=2007-04-14}}</ref>
[[Image:Cains Ballroom Tulsa.jpg|thumb|left|Cain's Ballroom came to be known as the "Carnegie Hall of Western Swing"<ref name="Cain's Ballroom">{{cite web | date=3-25-2007 | url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/webextra/itemsofinterest/centennial/centennial_storypage.asp?ID=070321_1_CE13_spanc63544| title= Cain’s Ballroom - A Music Icon: Venue is a landmark for Western swing, punk fans | format=web | work=Matt Elliot| pages=1 | publisher= Tulsa World| accessdate=2007-04-20}}</ref> during the 20th century.]]
The efforts of Tulsa businessman [[Cyrus Avery]], known the "Father of Route 66,"<ref name="Cyrus Avery">{{cite web | year=2007 | url=http://xroads.virginia.edu/~UG02/carney/avery.html | title=Cyrus Avery Page| work=Virginia University | page=1 | publisher=Virginia University | accessdate=2007-04-20}}</ref> further aided the 20th century growth. Avery began his campaign to create a road linking [[Chicago]] to [[California]] in Tulsa during the 1920's, earning the city the nickname "Birthplace of Route 66."<ref name="Plaza for Route 66">{{cite web | year=2007 | url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/article.aspx?articleID=070401_1_A1_spanc67632&breadcrumb=local| title=Plaza Kicks off Effort for Route 66| work=Brian Barber | page=1 | publisher=Tulsa World | accessdate=2007-04-27}}</ref> Once completed, [[Route 66]] took an important role in Tulsa's development as the city served as a popular rest stop for travelers, who were greeted by popular Tulsa Route 66 icons such as the Meadow Gold Sign and the [[Catoosa Blue Whale|Blue Whale]]. 

In [[1935]], [[Bob Willis]] and his group [[The Texas Playboys]] began playing at a small ballroom in downtown Tulsa. [[Cain's Ballroom]] later became the base for the group,<ref name="Cain's Ballroom">{{cite web | date=3-25-2007 | url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/webextra/itemsofinterest/centennial/centennial_storypage.asp?ID=070321_1_CE13_spanc63544| title= Cain’s Ballroom - A Music Icon: Venue is a landmark for Western swing, punk fans | format=web | work=Matt Elliot| pages=1 | publisher= Tulsa World| accessdate=2007-04-20}}</ref> which is largely credited for creating [[Western Swing]] music. As a result, Cain's Ballroom became a hub for the new kind of music. The venue continued to attract famous musicians throughout the 20th and 21st centuries, and is still in operation today.<ref name="Cain's Ballroom">{{cite web | date=3-25-2007 | url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/webextra/itemsofinterest/centennial/centennial_storypage.asp?ID=070321_1_CE13_spanc63544| title= Cain’s Ballroom - A Music Icon: Venue is a landmark for Western swing, punk fans | format=web | work=Matt Elliot| pages=1 | publisher= Tulsa World| accessdate=2007-04-20}}</ref>

Econoimic prosperity took a break in 1982, when a national recession greatly effected the oil industry in Tulsa. Areas of Texas and Oklahoma heavily dependant on oil began to see a freefall in gas prices and a mass exodus of oil industries. By 1987, national natural gas prices has dropped over 32% and crude oil prices had plummeted 46%.<ref name="Oil Bust">{{cite web | date=2006-01-23 | url= http://staging.okcommerce.gov/test1/dmdocuments/Oklahoma_Oil_Gas_Briefing_January_2006_0302061746.pdf| title= Oil and Gas Briefing| format=PDF | work=Oklahoma Department of Commerce| pages=1 | publisher= Oklahoma Department of Commerce | accessdate=2007-04-27}}</ref> Tulsa's economy, heavily dependant on the oil industry, was one of the hardest hit by the freefall of gas prices.<ref name="Oil Bust">{{cite web | date=2006-01-23 | url= http://staging.okcommerce.gov/test1/dmdocuments/Oklahoma_Oil_Gas_Briefing_January_2006_0302061746.pdf| title= Oil and Gas Briefing| format=PDF | work=Oklahoma Department of Commerce| pages=1 | publisher= Oklahoma Department of Commerce | accessdate=2007-04-27}}</ref> However, by 1992, Oklahoma's economy had fully recovered,<ref name="Oil Bust">{{cite web | date=2006-01-23 | url= http://staging.okcommerce.gov/test1/dmdocuments/Oklahoma_Oil_Gas_Briefing_January_2006_0302061746.pdf| title= Oil and Gas Briefing| format=PDF | work=Oklahoma Department of Commerce| pages=1 | publisher= Oklahoma Department of Commerce | accessdate=2007-04-27}}</ref> and leaders would attempt to expand the state into sectors unrelated to oil and energy.
 
Following the "oil bust," the title of "Oil Capital of the World" was relinquished to [[Houston]], but Tulsa city leaders worked to diversify the city from a largely petroleum-based economy to one based on energy, telecommunications, technology, education, and aviation. Efforts by city leaders led to the passage of the "Vision 2025" program in 2003 with the purpose of enhancing and revitalizing Tulsa's infrastructure and tourism industry. The keystone project of Vision 2025 was the construction of the [[BOK Center]] in downtown Tulsa. The multi-purpose arena, designed by famed architect [[Cesar Pelli]], is intended to be a home for the city's minor league hockey and arena football teams, as well as a venue for major concerts and conventions. Groundbreaking on the structure occurred in 2005 and completion is expected in 2008.<ref name="Tulsa Visitors Convention - BOK Center">{{cite web | date=2007 | url= http://ww3.visittulsa.com/general.asp?id=207| title= BOK Center| format=web | work=Tulsa Convention and Visitors bureau| pages=1 | publisher= Tulsa Convention and Visitors Bureau | accessdate=2007-04-20}}</ref>

In 2004, Tulsa was selected as the site of "[[The American]]," the world's largest free-standing statue, to be constructed on Holmes Peak near downtown.<ref name="'The American' Progressing">{{cite web | date=2007-04-24 | url=http://kotv.com/news/local/story/?id=125807| title= Progress On The American Slow But Steady | format=web | work=KOTV| pages=1 | publisher=KOTV | accessdate=2007-04-28}}</ref> Originally slated for completion in 2007, developers have recently announced a new expected unveiling in 2011, with construction beginning in 2007.<ref name="'The American' Progressing">{{cite web | date=2007-04-24 | url=http://kotv.com/news/local/story/?id=125807| title= Progress On The American Slow But Steady | format=web | work=KOTV| pages=1 | publisher=KOTV | accessdate=2007-04-28}}</ref> The statue will eventually stand 217&nbsp;feet, or about 60&nbsp;feet taller than the [[Statue of Liberty]] in New York City,<ref name="The American">{{cite web | date=2007| url=http://www.theamerican.com/home/index.cfm?&Flash=1| title= The American | format=web | work=The American Project| pages=1 | publisher=The American Project | accessdate=2007-04-28}}</ref> and attract an expected 1.5 million visitors to Tulsa annually.<ref name="'The American' Progressing">{{cite web | date=2007-04-24 | url=http://kotv.com/news/local/story/?id=125807| title= Progress On The American Slow But Steady | format=web | work=KOTV| pages=1 | publisher=KOTV | accessdate=2007-04-28}}</ref> The 21-story monument of a [[Native American]] man stretching his hand to an eagle is anticipated by developers to be a national icon.<ref name="Vision 2025: The American">{{cite web | year=2007 | url=http://www.vision2025.info/category.php?category=theamerican| title= The American| format=web | work=Vision 2025 Commission| pages=1 | publisher=Vision 2025 Commission| accessdate=2007-04-28}}</ref>

==Law and Government==
{{main|Government of Tulsa, Oklahoma}}

Tulsa is the county seat of [[Tulsa County]], and has a [[Mayor-council government|mayor-council form of government]]. This form of government has been in place since 1989, at which time Tulsa converted from a city commission form of government.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tulsacouncil.org/about_cc.php | title=About the Tulsa City Council | publisher=The Tulsa City Council| year=2007 | accessdate=2007-04-17}}</ref> The mayor is elected to a four-year term by [[Plurality voting system|plurality voting]]. There are nine city councilors, and each hold a two year term. The city of Tulsa lies mostly within [[Oklahoma's 1st congressional district|Oklahoma's 1st Congressional District]], with its far northwestern areas within [[Oklahoma's 3rd congressional district|Oklahoma's 3rd Congressional District]].
[[Image:Tulsa County Courthouse.jpg|thumb|right|The Tulsa County Courthouse serves as the base for most county government functions.]]
Tulsa's Mayor is appointed by a city-wide election, and each of the nine city councilors are elected from their own respective districts based on [[Plurality voting system|Pluarality voting]]. The present mayor of Tulsa is [[Kathy Taylor|Kathryn "Kathy" Taylor]], who previously served as Secretary of Commerce and Tourism for the state of Oklahoma. Taylor, a Democrat, unseated William LaFortune, a Republican, in April 2006. Another former Tulsa mayor, [[Jim Inhofe]], now represents Oklahoma in the [[United States Senate]]. The city auditor is elected independently of the City Council and Mayor to ensure that the auditor can act in an objective manner. This position serves a term of two years. The current auditor of Tulsa is Phil Wood, a Democrat. The city's legislative body is the City Council, which serves to pass laws, approve the city budget, and manage efficiency in city government. Roscoe Turner of District 3 currently serves as the council Chairman along with Vice Chairman John Eagleton of District 7.

Law in Tulsa is enforced by the Tulsa Police Department, an organization that has about 770 officers as of 2006.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.vachiefs.org/vacp/jobs/vacp_job_Tulsa.html | title=Police Chief – Tulsa, OK| publisher=Virginia Association of Cheifs of Police| year=2007 | accessdate=2007-04-29}}</ref> In 2005, Tulsa's total crime per 100,000 people was 6513.5,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://tulsa.areaconnect.com/crime1.htm| title=Tulsa OK Crime Statistics (2005 Crime Data) | publisher=Tulsa Area Connect| year=2007 | accessdate=2007-04-29}}</ref> which is about 1.5 times the national average.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cityrating.com/citycrime.asp?city=Tulsa&state=OK | title= Tulsa Crime Report| publisher=City Rating| year=2007 | accessdate=2007-04-29}}</ref> The city witnessed 61 murders, 891 robberies, and 6,403 burglaries in 2004.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cityrating.com/citycrime.asp?city=Tulsa&state=OK | title= Tulsa Crime Report| publisher=City Rating| year=2007 | accessdate=2007-04-29}}</ref>

