==Geography==
[[Image:Tulsa_skyline.JPG|thumb|left|250px|The Tulsa skyline dominates views from Turkey Mountain.]]
Tulsa is located in the northeastern corner of [[Oklahoma]], situated between the edge of the [[Great Plains]] and the foot of the [[Ozark Mountains]] in a generally forested region of rolling hills. The city serves as the gateway to "[[Green Country]]," a popular and officially designated name for northeast Oklahoma. The phrase stems from the region's dense green vegetation and relatively high amount of hills and lakes compared to that of Central and Western areas of Oklahoma,<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.pbs.org/newshour/vote2004/key-races/ok_profile.html | publisher=PBS | title=Vote 2004: Oklahoma Profile | accessdate=2007-04-30}}</ref> which have geography similar to "[[Great Plains|the Great Plains]]" region. Northeastern Oklahoma is the most topographically diverse part of the state, containing more than half of the state's registered state parks, six of its 11 ecosystems, more than a dozen major reservoirs, as well as the state's most diversified agricultural economy and outdoor sports and recreation industry.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.travelok.com/atv/index.asp#map | publisher=Oklahoma Department of Tourism | title=Oklahoma, The All-Terrain Vacation | accessdate=2007-04-20 }}</ref> The [[Geographic coordinate system|geographic coordinates]] of the city of Tulsa are {{coor dms|36|7|53|N|95|56|14|W|city}} (36.131294, -95.937332){{GR|1}}, with an elevation of 213&nbsp;meters (700&nbsp;ft) above [[sea level]]. 
[[Image:Tulsa satellite poster.jpg|thumb|right|As seen from space, most of Tulsa lies east of the Arkansas River.]]
===Topography===
The city is split by the prominent [[Arkansas River]], which flows in a wide, sandy-bottomed channel. Its flow through the Tulsa area is controlled by upstream flood-control reservoirs, but its width and depth can vary widely throughout the year, such as during periods of high rainfall or severe drought. However, a low-water dam maintains a full channel at all times in the area adjacent to downtown Tulsa. Heavily wooded and with abundant parks and water areas, the city holds several prominent hills with names such as "Shadow Mountain" and "Turkey Mountain," which create varied terrain within the city itself, especially in its southern portions. While the city's central and northern sections are generally flat to gently undulating, the Osage Hills extension into the northwestern part of the city further varies the landscape. Holmes Peak, the future site of [[The American]] monument in the northwest corner of the city, is the tallest point in five counties at 1030&nbsp;ft (314&nbsp;m).<ref>{{cite web | url= http://theamerican.com/location/index.cfm| publisher=The American Project| title=Holmes Peak| accessdate=2007-04-29 }}</ref>

According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of 483.9&nbsp;[[square kilometers]] (186.8&nbsp;[[square mile|mi²]]). 473.1 square kilometers&nbsp;(182.6&nbsp;mi²) of it is land and 10.9&nbsp;square kilometers (4.2&nbsp;mi²) of it (2.24%) is water.

===Climate===
Tulsa is situated near the heart of [[Tornado Alley]], and has a [[temperate]] climate typical of the [[Continental climate|continental]] variety, with a yearly average temperature of 61°F.<ref name="Weather year in Review 2003">{{cite web | date=2004 | url= http://www.srh.noaa.gov/tsa/2003_year_in_review.html| title= NOAA Year in Review - Tulsa, OK| format=web | work=NOAA| pages=1 | publisher= National Weather Service | accessdate=2006-04-15}}</ref> As is typical for the temperate zones, Tulsa's climate varies throughout the seasons and experiences occasional extremes.
[[Image:Lightning over Tulsa.jpg|thumb|left|Lighting over downtown Tulsa is a common sight in during the spring months.]]
[[Summer]] temperatures of 40 °C, or 100 °F, or higher are often observed from July to early September. These are usually accompanied by high humidity, caused by warm air from the [[Gulf of Mexico]] brought in by southerly winds. Between May and September, Tulsa also experiences an "[[Ozone]] Season", caused by a combination of factors including climate and [[hydrocarbon]] emissions. During this season, Tulsa frequently issues "Ozone Alerts", encouraging all parties to do their part in complying with the [[Clean Air Act]] and [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|E.P.A.]] standards. [[Winter]] temperatures, while generally mild, also occasionally experience extremes below -20 °C, or 0 °F. The [[Autumn|fall]] season is quite short, consisting of a brief period of pleasant, sunny days followed by cool nights. Primarily during the [[Spring (season)|spring]] and early [[summer]] months, the Tulsa area is often subjected to severe [[thunderstorms]], some of which contain large [[hail]], damaging winds and, not infrequently, small [[tornadoes]]. Severe weather is not limited, though, to this season. On [[December 5]] [[1975]], for example, Tulsa experienced a tornado.<ref name="The Climate of Tulsa Country">{{cite web | date=Dec. 2003 |url= http://climate.ocs.ou.edu/county_climate/Products/County_Climatologies/county_climate_tulsa.pdf| title= Climate of Tulsa County| format=web | work=Oklahoma Climatological Survey| pages=1 | publisher= Oklahoma Climatological Survey | accessdate=2006-04-26}}</ref> The spring and early summer [[thunderstorm]] pattern also provides the area with a disproportionate share of its annual [[rainfall]], with yearly totals averaging around 99&nbsp;centimeters (39.&nbsp;in).<ref name=Weatherbase>{{cite web | url =http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=065327&refer= |title= Weatherbase: Historical Weather for Tulsa, Oklahoma, United States of America | publisher=Weatherbase | year=2007 | accessdate=2007-04-26 | language = English }}</ref> Due to frequent [[flood|flooding]] in past decades, Tulsa now has one of the most extensive flood control systems in the nation. In 2000, [[Federal Emergency Management Agency|FEMA]] honored Tulsa as leading the nation in flood plain management.<ref>{{cite press release | publisher=[[Federal Emergency Management Agency|FEMA]] | title=FEMA Honors Tulsa, Oklahoma As Nation's Leading Floodplain Management Community (News Release HQ-00-046a) | date=[[2000-09-13]] | url=http://www.fema.gov/news/newsrelease.fema?id=8679 | accessdate=2007-04-28}}</ref>

